WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.540 --> 00:00:04.360
Neural networks are a powerful class of machine learning algorithms

2
00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:05.920
and they come in many varieties

3
00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:08.740
there's no way to give appropriate attention to neural networks

4
00:00:08.740 --> 00:00:09.900
in an introductory video

5
00:00:09.900 --> 00:00:13.380
like this here we will only identify a few key components

6
00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:15.820
of a neural network and the overall work flow

7
00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:20.120
so we can understand how quantum computing can contribute

8
00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:23.579
the neural network is a connected graph of neurons

9
00:00:23.580 --> 00:00:26.580
a neuron is basically just a thing that holds a number

10
00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:29.840
and that number is often called an activation how

11
00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:32.440
on or off the neuron is

12
00:00:32.440 --> 00:00:34.940
the neurons are sorted in two layers

13
00:00:34.940 --> 00:00:37.460
and the first layer is the input layer

14
00:00:37.460 --> 00:00:39.840
and the last is the output layer

15
00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:42.760
in between there are layers used in processing called

16
00:00:42.760 --> 00:00:45.619
hidden layers the activation of the

17
00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:49.260
input layer is just loaded directly from the data to be analyzed

18
00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:52.520
such as the pixel shading in an image

19
00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:55.980
the next hidden layer's activations are determined

20
00:00:55.980 --> 00:00:58.160
by the neurons in the input layer

21
00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:02.040
and by weights symbolized by the lines connecting all the neurons

22
00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:03.920
in the input layer to all the neurons in the

23
00:01:03.920 --> 00:01:07.479
next layer in other words we determine the activation

24
00:01:07.480 --> 00:01:09.720
of a neuron in the hidden layer

25
00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:11.780
by a awaited sum of all the

26
00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:14.440
input activations we can

27
00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:17.000
also apply a bias a shift

28
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:18.720
we might want to activate a neuron

29
00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:21.560
in the hidden layer not just if the weighted sum is

30
00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:26.180
positive but only if it exceeds a large threshold

31
00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:29.839
we then often apply a complicated function to obtain an activation

32
00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:33.680
between zero and one like a hyperbolic tangent

33
00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:35.120
or sometimes differently a

34
00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:37.980
rectified linear unit you don't need to worry

35
00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:39.920
too much about these right now the only

36
00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.880
thing important to note here about these functions

37
00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:44.640
is that they are non linear

38
00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:47.920
so that the network as a whole contains both linear

39
00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:50.699
and nonlinear components

40
00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:54.000
the same waited some of activations this time

41
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:55.520
starting with the activations of the

42
00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:58.180
first hidden layer in the new weights

43
00:01:58.180 --> 00:02:01.620
extends up to the next hidden layer

44
00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:06.080
this continues to the final layer which is an output

45
00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:08.860
the output layer has neurons corresponding to

46
00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:12.139
categories and the activations tell us

47
00:02:12.140 --> 00:02:15.900
how certain the network is of the classification

48
00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:19.740
so the output categories in an image analysis might be

49
00:02:19.740 --> 00:02:23.000
dog cat hamster and so on

50
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.020
and an activation of point nine five on the

51
00:02:26.020 --> 00:02:28.920
dog neuron would indicate a high degree of certainty that

52
00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:32.779
the image is of a dog you might start your neural network

53
00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:34.120
with a random set of weights

54
00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:38.240
and biases or from the known reasonable starting configuration

55
00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:40.120
but then the idea is to check

56
00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:42.900
how well your neural network classifies things

57
00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:47.040
and improve it we use a cost function to describe

58
00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:49.620
how our neural network deviates from

59
00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:52.760
correct classification this involves taking the

60
00:02:52.760 --> 00:02:55.519
difference between the actual value of an image

61
00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:58.020
say for example a value of one on the neuron

62
00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:01.860
for dog and zero on all other output nerons

63
00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:04.080
and the predicted values

64
00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.040
we some over all the categories

65
00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:09.240
so we track not only whether the right category was

66
00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:10.920
most activated but we can

67
00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:15.000
also track if incorrect activations are reduced

68
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.739
within some over all the examples in our training set

69
00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:20.560
and obtain a cost we then

70
00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:23.580
vary the parameters like the weights in each layer

71
00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:27.820
between all neurons and the biases on all their owns

72
00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:30.480
classical optimisation routines are used

73
00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:34.700
to search for a local minimum in the cost function

74
00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:37.720
if nothing is done to reduce the complexity of this

75
00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:38.719
you can imagine what an

76
00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:42.140
astronomical parameter space we've set up here

77
00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:45.220
consider a neural network designed to analyze images with

78
00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:49.240
just a thousand pixels this neural network might have a thousand

79
00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:52.220
input neurons just a single hidden layer

80
00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:55.660
and binary output like cat or dog

81
00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:57.460
this is the very simplest case

82
00:03:57.460 --> 00:04:00.879
and still corresponds to a thousand by a thousand

83
00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.480
or million weights between the input in hidden layers

84
00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:06.840
and another two thousand between the

85
00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:08.600
hidden and output layers

86
00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:10.000
possibly also a thousand or

87
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.500
so biases so this simple neural network would correspond

88
00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:16.860
to well over a million parameters thou to be fair

89
00:04:16.860 --> 00:04:20.140
modern algorithms typically do make simplifications

90
00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:21.859
in classical neural networks

91
00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:24.720
and there are whole fields devoted to making this minimisation

92
00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:27.100
possible and even efficient

93
00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:29.180
but the fact remains that this is a very

94
00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:31.020
high dimensional problem

95
00:04:31.020 --> 00:04:32.520
and training a neural network

96
00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:33.700
can be very time consuming

97
00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:37.560
and costly a quantum neural network or qnn

98
00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:40.600
works by first loading the input data

99
00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:42.559
and then applying quantum circuits

100
00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:45.560
corresponding to weights between layers

101
00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:48.700
and finally a layer of measurement

102
00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:51.600
a few key points about this the data

103
00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:54.900
loading and the waitings are linear operations

104
00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:57.360
but the measurements are nonlinear

105
00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:00.220
so as in classical neural networks we have

106
00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:03.699
both linear and nonlinear components

107
00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:05.500
also the weight circuits

108
00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.740
still have variational parameters

109
00:05:07.740 --> 00:05:12.500
so there is still a classical minimisation to be carried out

110
00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:15.120
of course this has only scratched the surface of quantum neural

111
00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:18.500
networks but we hope you continue learning about the applications

112
00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:19.620
of quantum neural networks

113
00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:21.820
and other quantity machine learning applications

114
